and this collapse warms up the centre of the
protostar

219
00:20:43,919 --> 00:20:48,730
up to the point of starting the reactions
of nuclear fusion of hydrogen into helium.

220
00:20:48,730 --> 00:20:52,690
They spend most of their life burning hydrogen
into helium.

221
00:20:52,690 --> 00:20:56,210
At this stage, they are located on the main
sequence we talked about

222
00:20:56,210 --> 00:21:01,330
several times, which is a mass sequence
with the most massive stars at the top

223
00:21:01,330 --> 00:21:06,470
and the least massive stars at the bottom.
Once the hydrogen has been consumed, the equilibrium

224
00:21:06,470 --> 00:21:10,539
between the
gas and radiative pressure outwards and gravity

225
00:21:10,539 --> 00:21:13,340
in the opposite direction
is broken.

226
00:21:13,340 --> 00:21:20,429
The core of the star tends to collapse
while the outer layers expand

227
00:21:20,429 --> 00:21:26,099
and the star becomes therefore a giant star.
At this stage, it undergoes a succesive series

228
00:21:26,099 --> 00:21:29,289
of contractions
and ignitions of nuclear reactions

229
00:21:29,289 --> 00:21:35,690
that each produces heavier and heavier elements.
If the star is beyond 8 solar masses, it explodes

230
00:21:35,690 --> 00:21:40,049
in a supernova, a remain of which we see here
in the background.

231
00:21:40,049 --> 00:21:45,429
If the star is below 8 solar masses
such as our Sun with one solar mass,

232
00:21:45,429 --> 00:21:49,270
it produces a nebula such as the nebula Messier
57

233
00:21:49,270 --> 00:21:52,529
that we have already seen in the first chapter,
at the center of which

234
00:21:52,529 --> 00:21:57,509
rests a white dwarf.
Finally, stars with very low masses, less

235
00:21:57,509 --> 00:22:03,090
than 0.08 solar masses,
remain as red dwarves

236
00:22:03,090 --> 00:22:06,320
or brown dwarves at the bottom of the colour-magnitude
diagram

237
00:22:06,320 --> 00:22:08,730
and they will keep shining for billions of
years.

